Circle of Fifths

The Circle of Fifths shows the relationship between the 12 tones of the chromatic scale. Moving clockwise, each key is a perfect 5th higher. Moving counter-clockwise, each key is a perfect 4th higher (or 5th lower).

Key Signatures:
‚Ä¢ Sharps (clockwise): G, D, A, E, B, F‚ôØ, C‚ôØ
‚Ä¢ Flats (counter-clockwise): F, B‚ô≠, E‚ô≠, A‚ô≠, D‚ô≠, G‚ô≠, C‚ô≠

Relative Minor: Each major key's relative minor is 3 half-steps down (inner circle).

Scales

A scale is a sequence of notes in ascending or descending order. The pattern of whole (W) and half (H) steps defines the scale type.

Major Scale (Ionian)
Pattern: W - W - H - W - W - W - H
Example: C D E F G A B C
Sound: Happy, bright, resolved
Natural Minor Scale (Aeolian)
Pattern: W - H - W - W - H - W - W
Example: A B C D E F G A
Sound: Sad, dark, introspective
Harmonic Minor Scale
Pattern: W - H - W - W - H - 1¬Ω - H
Example: A B C D E F G‚ôØ A
Sound: Exotic, tension, classical
Pentatonic Major
Notes: 1 - 2 - 3 - 5 - 6 (skip 4th and 7th)
Example: C D E G A C
Sound: Folk, Asian, rock solos
Blues Scale (Hexatonic)
Notes: 1 - ‚ô≠3 - 4 - ‚ô≠5 - 5 - ‚ô≠7
Example: C E‚ô≠ F G‚ô≠ G B‚ô≠ C
Sound: Classic blues, rock
Blues Scale (9-note)
Notes: 1 - 2 - ‚ô≠3 - 3 - 4 - ‚ô≠5 - 5 - 6 - ‚ô≠7
Example: C D E‚ô≠ E F G‚ô≠ G A B‚ô≠ C
Sound: Rich, jazzy blues with major/minor blend

The 7 Modes

Modes are scales derived from the major scale, each starting on a different degree. They create unique moods and colors in music.

I. Ionian (Major Scale)
Pattern: W-W-H-W-W-W-H
C D E F G A B C
Happy, bright ‚Ä¢ Pop, classical, folk
II. Dorian (Minor with raised 6th)
Pattern: W-H-W-W-W-H-W
D E F G A B C D
Jazzy minor ‚Ä¢ Jazz, funk, "So What"
III. Phrygian (Minor with ‚ô≠2)
Pattern: H-W-W-W-H-W-W
E F G A B C D E
Spanish, exotic ‚Ä¢ Flamenco, metal
IV. Lydian (Major with #4)
Pattern: W-W-W-H-W-W-H

Dreamy, floating ‚Ä¢ Film scores, prog rock
V. Mixolydian (Major with ‚ô≠7)
Pattern: W-W-H-W-W-H-W
G A B C D E F G
Bluesy major ‚Ä¢ Rock, blues, "Sweet Home Alabama"
VI. Aeolian (Natural Minor)
Pattern: W-H-W-W-H-W-W

VII. Locrian (Diminished)

Chord Functions

In a key, each chord has a function that creates tension or resolution. Understanding these helps you predict chord progressions.

Tonic (I) - Home
The "home base" chord. Feels stable and resolved.
In C major: C major
Subdominant (IV) - Away
Creates gentle movement away from home.
In C major: F major
Dominant (V) - Tension
Creates strong tension that wants to resolve to I.
In C major: G major (or G7)
Chord Inversions (same notes, different bass)

Inversions change which note is lowest, giving chords different colors while using the same notes.

Root Position
C-E-G (root on bottom)
1st Inversion
E-G-C (3rd on bottom)
2nd Inversion
G-C-E (5th on bottom)

Rhythm Basics

Rhythm is the pattern of sounds and silences in music. Understanding note values and time signatures is essential for reading and playing music.

Each note type represents a different duration. In 4/4 time:

Time Signatures

The top number = beats per measure. The bottom = which note gets one beat.

4/4 (Common Time)
4 quarter-note beats per measure ‚Ä¢ Pop, rock, most music
3/4 (Waltz Time)
3 quarter-note beats ‚Ä¢ Waltzes, ballads
6/8 (Compound Duple)
2 groups of 3 eighth notes ‚Ä¢ "House of the Rising Sun"
2/4 (March Time)
2 quarter-note beats ‚Ä¢ Marches, polkas
